## 🧠 1. MODULE STRUCTURES (STATIC VIEW)

### 🧩 Intuition
Think of a system as a **map of dependencies**:  
“Who needs who to exist?”

### 📘 Uses Relationship
**✅ Definition**  
A *uses* relationship means: one module depends on another module to function.

**🧠 Key Idea**  
If **A uses B**, then:
- A depends on B
- If B changes → A may break

### 🔥 Keras Example

```python
model = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Dense(4)
])
```

**Dependencies:**

```mermaid
graph TD
    Model --> Layer
    Layer --> Ops
    Ops --> Backend
```

### 💡 Architectural Insight
Uses relationships help you:
- Understand impact of changes
- Track dependencies
- Control complexity

### 🏗️ Layered Architecture

**🧩 Intuition**  
Think of floors in a building:
- Top floor uses lower floors
- Lower floors don’t depend on upper floors

**✅ Definition**  
A system is **layered** when:
- Each layer has a clear role
- Each layer only uses the one below it

**🔥 Keras Layers (Real)**

| Layer    | Responsibility              |
|----------|-----------------------------|
| Model    | Orchestrates                |
| Layer    | Defines computation         |
| Ops      | Provides math               |
| Backend  | Executes                    |

**🧱 Diagram**

```mermaid
graph TD
    Model --> Layer
    Layer --> Ops
    Ops --> Backend
```

### ⚠️ Why Dependency Direction Matters

**🧩 Intuition**  
Dependencies must go **DOWN**, not up

**❌ Bad Design**

```mermaid
graph TD
    Backend --> Layer
    Layer --> Model
```

→ Low-level controls high-level → **unstable**

**✅ Good Design**

```mermaid
graph TD
    Model --> Layer
    Layer --> Ops
    Ops --> Backend
```

**🧠 Key Rule**  
High-level modules should **NOT** depend on low-level details directly

**🔥 Keras Insight**  
Keras avoids:

```python
Layer → TensorFlow directly   ❌
```

Instead:

```python
Layer → ops → backend         ✅
```

**This allows:**
- Backend switching (TF → JAX → PyTorch…)
- Clean modularity
- High portability

